This page is a supplementary teaching scaffold for dormant root work and entry assembly.

## Compilation versus activation

Every selected normal module compiles its dormant root work once.

The compiler synthesises a non-exported, non-importable and infallible `start` for top-level runtime work. Compilation does not execute it.

An entry assembly later selects one already compiled normal module and activates only that module's root work and entry metadata.

There are no active-root and imported-root parser modes. Importers never receive or suppress another module's root payload.

## Page fragments

- Runtime fragments remain executable work in `start`.
- Compile-time fragments fold into module compiler metadata.
- Each folded fragment records its runtime insertion index.
- The HTML builder merges compile-time and runtime fragments in source order.
- HIR does not carry compile-time document structure.

Support modules and the project package facade have no root activity.

## Rewrite focus

Explain compilation versus linking, dormant initialisers, entry points and why document assembly belongs outside semantic IR.

Canonical details live in both architecture authorities.
